The Data

For this tutorial, we are using the penguins dataset from the palmerpenguins R package maintained by Dr.Allison Horst. This data contains measurements and other characteristics for 344 penguins observed near Palmer Station Antarctica. The data were originally collected by Dr.Kristen Gorman. Click here to view the codebook for this data set.

library(palmerpenguins)
glimpse(penguins)
## Rows: 344
## Columns: 8

## $ island            <fct> Torgersen, Torgersen, Torgersen, Torgersen, Torgers
## $ bill_length_mm    <dbl> 39.1, 39.5, 40.3, NA, 36.7, 39.3, 38.9, 39.2, 34.1,

There are some observations with missing values for the measurements, so we will remove those for the purposes of this analysis:

penguins <- penguins %>%
  drop_na()

Exploratory data analysis

We will use k-nearest neighbor to classify the penguins into three groups based on their measurements. Before performing the classification, lets do a brief exploratory data analysis to take a look at the data.

We will use body_mass_g, bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm, and flipper_length_mm to classify the penguins, so well focus on these variables.

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = species)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "cyan4") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Penguin Species")

We can use the ggpairs function in the GGally package to quickly view the relationship between the measurements well use for classification.

library(GGally)
penguins %>%
  select(species, body_mass_g, bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm, flipper_length_mm) %>%
  ggpairs(aes(color = species))

k-nearest neighbor

Suppose we have the measurements for 3 new penguins but we dont know their species. We can use k-nearest neighbors to predict the class for the new penguins by taking the plurality vote of its k nearest neighbors in terms of their class (species) memberships.

Here is the data for the three new penguins:

Body Mass Bill Length Bill Depth Flipper Length
Penguin 1 3706 38.8 18.3 190
Penguin 2 3733 46.3 17.5 191
Penguin 3 3950 47.4 15 216 
new_penguins <- tibble(body_mass_g = c(3706, 3733, 3950), 
                       bill_length_mm = c(38.8, 46.3, 47.4), 
                       bill_depth_mm = c(18.3, 17.5, 15), 
                       flipper_length_mm = c(190, 191, 216))

We will use the knn() function from the class package.

For the knn we need to create a vector of the species in our data.

species <- penguins %>%
  select(species) %>%
  pull()

We will also create a new data frame that only contains the measurements were using for the k-nearest neighbor. By using the ends_with option in the select function, we can select bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm, and flipper_length_mm without typing each variable name individually.

penguins_knn <- penguins %>%
  select(body_mass_g, ends_with("_mm"))

Now were ready to perform k-nearest neighbor. Since we know there are three species of penguins in the data set, we will set k = 3 to specify there are three classes.

library(class)

knn_species <- knn(penguins_knn, new_penguins, species, k = 3, prob = FALSE)

We assign the function output to the object knn_species. This is a vector of the predicted species for our three new penguins.

knn_species
## [1] Adelie    Adelie    Chinstrap
## Levels: Adelie Chinstrap Gentoo

Using k-nearest neighbors,

  • Penguin 1 is predicted to be in the Adelie species.
  • Penguin 2 is predicted to be in the Adelie species.
  • Penguin 3 is predicted to be in the Chinstrap species.
